The Pima indian dataset

In first place, let us load the Pima.tr and Pima.te datasets which are available in the MASS R package.

Pima <- rbind(MASS::Pima.tr, MASS::Pima.te)
y <- as.numeric(Pima$type == "Yes") # Binary response
X <- model.matrix(type ~ . - 1, data = Pima) # Design matrix
X <- cbind(1, X) # Standardize the data

To fix the ideas, we are interested in the Bayesian counterpart of the following models for binary data:

# Probit model
fit_probit <- glm(type ~ X - 1, family = binomial(link = "probit"), data = Pima)
# Logit model
fit_logit <- glm(type ~ X - 1, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = Pima)

The focus of this presentation is on the computational aspects, so we will employ a relatively vague prior centered at \(0\), namely \(\beta \sim N(0, 100 I_p)\). The reader should be aware that much better alternatives exist for example if one aims at specifying an uninformative prior.

In first place, we specify the log-likelihood and the log-posterior functions. We consider here the logistic case.

# Loglikelihood of a logistic regression model
loglik <- function(beta, y, X) {
  eta <- c(X %*% beta)
  sum(y * eta - log(1 + exp(eta)))
}

# Logposterior
logpost <- function(beta, y, X) {
  loglik(beta, y, X) + sum(dnorm(beta, 0, 10, log = T))
}

# Gradient
lgradient <- function(beta, y, X) {
  probs <- plogis(c(X %*% beta))
  c(crossprod(X, y - probs))
}

MALA algoritm

# R represent the number of samples
# burn_in is the number of discarded samples
# s is a tuning parameter
MALA <- function(R, burn_in, y, X, s) {
  p <- ncol(X)
  out <- matrix(0, R, p) # Initialize an empty matrix to store the values
  beta <- rep(0, p) # Initial values

  sigma2 <- s^2 / p^(1 / 3)
  sigma <- sqrt(sigma2)

  # Starting the Gibbs sampling
  for (r in 1:(burn_in + R)) {
    beta_new <- beta + sigma2 / 2 * lgradient(beta, y, X) + rnorm(p, 0, sigma)
    lpart <- logpost(beta_new, y, X) - logpost(beta, y, X)
    qpart <- sum(dnorm(beta, beta_new + sigma2 / 2 * lgradient(beta_new, y, X), sigma, log = T)) - sum(dnorm(beta_new, beta + sigma2 / 2 * lgradient(beta, y, X), sigma, log = T))
    alpha <- min(1, exp(lpart + qpart))
    if (runif(1) < alpha) {
      beta <- beta_new # Accept the value
    }
    # Store the values after the burn-in period
    if (r > burn_in) {
      out[r - burn_in, ] <- beta
    }
  }
  out
}

MALA

library(coda)
R <- 30000
burn_in <- 30000
set.seed(123)

s <- 0.18 # After some trial ad error

# Running the MCMC
fit_MCMC <- as.mcmc(MALA(R = R, burn_in = burn_in, y, X, s)) # Convert the matrix into a "coda" object

Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (Stan)

data {
  int<lower=0> n;   // number of data items
  int<lower=0> p;   // number of predictors
  matrix[n, p] X;   // predictor matrix
  int<lower=0,upper=1> y[n];
}
parameters {
  vector[p] beta;       // coefficients for predictors
}
model {
  y ~ bernoulli_logit(X * beta);
}
library(rstan)
set.seed(123)
fit_HMC <- stan(
  file = "logistic.stan", # Stan program
  data = list(X = X, y = y, n = nrow(X), p = ncol(X)), # named list of data
  chains = 1, # number of Markov chains
  warmup = burn_in, # Burn-in iterations per chain
  iter = R + burn_in # Total number of iterations per chain
)
